{
  "description": {
    "title": "Competitive clearing under a declining cap (the hello-world)",
    "economic_framing": "One carbon market, three compliance entities with distinct marginal-abatement-cost (MAC) slopes, cleared competitively year by year (no banking, each year is an independent static auction). The cap declines 10 Mt/yr from 180 to 130 Mt over 2025-2030, forcing more abatement each year and lifting the allowance price along the aggregate MAC curve.",
    "mechanism": "Each firm i abates a_i(P) = min(max_abatement_i, P / cost_slope_i) and buys allowances for its residual emissions (no free allocation). The market price is the P at which aggregate residual demand equals the auctioned cap: sum_i (E0_i - a_i(P)) = cap. As the cap tightens the required abatement rises, so P climbs the merit order Power (slope 2) -> Steel (slope 4) -> Cement (slope 6).",
    "participants": "Power E0=100 Mt (max abate 50, slope 2), Steel E0=60 Mt (max abate 30, slope 4), Cement E0=40 Mt (max abate 15, slope 6). BAU total 200 Mt; total abatement capacity 95 Mt.",
    "expected_output": {
      "Equilibrium Carbon Price 2025-2030 [USD/tCO2]": [
        21.818181818181785,
        32.727272727272684,
        43.63636363636368,
        54.545454545454575,
        65.45454545454542,
        76.36363636363637
      ],
      "Total Abatement 2025-2030 [Mt]": [20.0, 30.0, 40.0, 50.0, 60.0, 70.0],
      "reading": "Monotone-rising price as the cap tightens: at cap 180 only 20 Mt of abatement is needed (cheap, ~21.8 USD); at cap 130 the required 70 Mt climbs the steeper part of the aggregate MAC (~76.4 USD). A pure textbook competitive cap-and-trade path."
    }
  },
